evaluation.response:
I can understand why you might feel a conflict between what a mental health professional has said about you, and what an AI coach has suggested. Both perspectives can have some validity, based on the data each one has about you.

**A mental health professional** would have a more in-depth understanding of your overall mental health, based on a thorough evaluation and possibly some history. The temptation to "self-diagnose" or get a quick opinion from an AI can be pretty compelling, but understand that while AI coaches have access to a lot of data, they don't have the same level of training and expertise as a licensed therapist.

**An AI coach** might perform a quick online assessment and provide a simplified explanation of your symptoms or personality traits. They often can't get a comprehensive sense of who you are, or give a full diagnosis the way a therapist can.

Many things you're feeling or experiencing might align with a particular diagnosis, and could be caused by entirely different factors. In the case of someone feeling "sensitive/creative", those are also possible symptoms of high sensitivity or creativity - or they might be characteristics that coexist with some mental health challenges.&#x20;

It might be really helpful to speak with your therapist about your concerns, and get some insight from them about what it means that the AI gave you the feedback it did. Is it possible that its findings have some validity, but don't represent the full picture? Or is the AI possibly on to something that your therapist hasn't explored with you yet?&#x20;

I can see you're going through a tough time right now. Here are some potential steps you can take:

*   **Connect with others:**&#x20;
*   **Self-care:**&#x20;
*   **Reconnect with your addictions:**&#x20;
*   **Assess your coping habits:**

1.  Regardless of whether or not you're 'being tested,' the most effective thing you can do will be to run your own life and your own reality as much as possible, taking the time to figure out what behavior feels authentic and empowering to you. Let go as much as possible of pressures from others - you be you, and don't be afraid if the people around you struggle to understand or thrive in a world where we're all being our own selves.
2.  You deserve professional help if you're struggling with mental health challenges, to figure out what's going on and how to manage it. There are resources available - <https://www.crisistextline.org/>
3.  Seeking support can happen in many ways - in addition to a professional, consider a trusted person who loves you such as a parent, 'higher power', or close friend. Also consider trying to get enough sleep.&#x20;
